Thank you for all who joined us for today’s IG Live where @ihadamiscarriage and I spoke openly about the various components of grief and loss.

Our conversation included: 

*Jessica’s personal experience with pregnancy loss.

*How to support someone who has experienced loss.

*Ways to access support for grief.

*The importance of normalizing the grieving process.

Thank you @ihadamiscarriage for being so courageously open and transparent about your healing journey.

Today I had the opportunity to speak about panic attacks with @anxietyjosh, a UK psychotherapist and author.

Our conversation included:
*What are panic attacks?
*The physiological and psychological components of panic attacks. 
*The effectiveness of graded exposure.
*How to shift from avoidance and fear to curiosity and understanding.

Thank you so much for all who joined us and contributed to this fruitful conversation! 

#anxiety #panicattack #mentalhealth

For Day #15 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I got to speak with @refugeingrief about the topic of grief.

Our conversation included:

*Societal ideas about grief
*What does “being stuck” in grief mean.
*The importance of understanding the language we use around grief.
*Ways to normalize grief:

Thank you all who joined us today and each day of this wonderful month dedicated to mental health awareness!

#grief #griefjourney #loss

#trauma #healing #traumainformed

Thank you for all who participated and submitted questions prior to today’s live!

For Day #8 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I had the opportunity to speak with Eric @samehere_global about our shared advocacy work to change the conversation around mental health.

Our conversation included: 
*Why the current 1 in 5 statistic divides 
*How emotional & mental health education is currently being implemented in schools
*New ways to raise awareness 
*How to start shifting the conversation from illness to normalizing the fact that we all struggle.

Thank you for everyone who joined and helped facilitate this great conversation!

#samehere #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth

node.title: Changing the conversation around mental health with @samehere_global

node.text:
I was 22 years old the first time I lost a loved one to suicide.

He was my godfather and without a doubt my favorite human being.

It took me losing a family member to finally understand that the things I was taught about suicide were untrue.

We unfortunately still live in a society where suicide is labeled as “selfish” or “weak.”

In honor of National Suicide Prevention week, let’s commit to finally changing the conversation around suicide. 

Let’s humanize those who struggle with it.

Let’s offer support over judgement.

Let’s dedicate time to learn and educate ourselves about suicide.

I truly believe suicide is preventable but first we have to shift the way we think and talk about it. 

Let today be the day for each of us to do a little more to end the shame and stigma associated with suicide. 💚

#nationalsuicidepreventionweek #realconvo @afspnational @crisistextline @800273talk

node.text:
It’s hard for me to wrap my head around why we as a society continue to blame, judge or shame people who experience trauma.

No one chooses to be traumatized.

A trauma response occurs after we undergo events that overwhelm our system and hinders our ability to cope. 

Yet people continue to treat others as if they are choosing to struggle, with comments like “It’s not that big of a deal” or “Stop focusing on the past.” 

We need to stop shaming people who are trying to survive something that has greatly impacted them.

We need to stop judging people who are trying to manage intrusive thoughts, feelings and memories.

We need to stop blaming people who are struggling to find remnants of who they were before the trauma. 

I can’t stress this enough.

People don’t CHOOSE to be traumatized, so let’s stop treating them as if they do.

node.text:
One of the most misunderstood relationships is the one between mental health struggles and high achievements (sometimes referred to as high functioning). 

We continue to live in a society to that paints the picture of mental health struggles as the individual who is closed off to the world, unable to leave their bed.

And while these experiences absolutely exist, more often is the person who is successfully navigating life (school, work, family, friends) with the burden of emotional or mental pain weighing heavily on them.

It’s dangerous to assume that just because someone is successful or high achieving that they are living without mental health struggles.

Some of the most praised and admired people are also the ones who are actually struggling in silence the most. 

A gentle reminder that high achievements and mental health struggles are not mutually exclusive. 💚

node.text:
Imagine a world where we would call into a work and say we are using a mental health day.

No questions asked. No repercussions. Our job is protected because mental health days are a designated part of our sick leave.

Imagine a world where we would call into school and say we are taking a mental health day.

No doctor’s note required. No penalty for missing an assignment. Make up tests are permitted because mental health days are now a valid reason to miss a day of school.

Will mental health days be implemented in every school and workplace across the country starting tomorrow?

No.

But we can all play a part in normalizing mental health days and reminding others that mental health is health! 

*Next two slides make my heart happy and the workplace culture I dream of for all of us. 💚

node.text:
Swipe to read ⏩⏩⏩

This isn’t an anti-apology post.

I am all for apologizing and taking accountability when we are in the wrong.

This post is about removing the need to apologize for the things we struggle with.

When we apologize for our mental health struggles, we further ingrain our own sense of guilt and shame.

Yet when we shift from apologizing to thanking, we allow the people in our lives to know how much we appreciate them.

So let TODAY BE THE DAY that we stop apologizing for the things we struggle with. 💚
